 this is structured, but I want to explore how this all interacts.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering library handling**\\n\\nI’m thinking about how to manage library calls. I could include a branching option: if the mapLibraryName ends with .jnilib, I should call and assert dynlib; otherwise, I’ll use existing methods. I realize that the native external run on Linux won’t cover everything, so I need to focus on remaining options. I wonder if there will be a future for a Mac lane in this context. That could add complexity!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating library name handling**\\n\\nI'm considering how `System.mapLibraryName(name)` might function if it returns a string ending in .jnilib by passing it a name with trailing characters. It seems like it might not sanitize input. For Linux, \\\"foo\\\\n\\\" becomes \\\"libfoo\\\\n.so,\\\" so it should always suffix, but I'm curious about null inputs causing NPE or long strings causing overflow. An alternative could be to test the mapping process for .jnilib while ensuring the test logic remains intact for native images. Let's evaluate this further.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring test execution on emulated Mac**\\n\\nI'm considering if it's possible to run tests on an emulated Mac by using a custom classloader to load NativeLibraryLoader after modifying the \\\"os.name\\\" property. However, I'm thinking that `System.mapLibraryName` may reference the `os.name` constant, especially when used in a Native Image hosted at build time. If that’s the case, I might need to rethink this approach, as it likely won't work as expected. It's an interesting challenge to navigate!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_ZX0TI46pqva39AmgV7CdzWKI|fc_002b0d3570c69a040169f0ce515b58819c8819924336145ba2", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "git log --oneline -3 && git status --short && nl -ba tests/src/io.netty/netty-all/4.0.23.Final/src/test/java/io_netty/netty_all/Native