[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Considering Git Commits and Tests**\n\nI’m weighing whether to amend the current commit or create a new one based on the user's request after finishing. We already have a previous commit, so it seems I'll need a new one for any refinements. There’s a possibility of modifying a test with an additional method using a specific library, but it won't cover Linux. \n\nI’m thinking about maximizing coverage and noting that they want a second attempt. Maybe a dedicated test documenting platform branches could work, but I'm curious whether external sources will accept it. I'll need to avoid running or compiling tests.\n\n**Exploring Native Library Loading Options**\n\nI'm trying to explore how `System.mapLibraryName` behaves in Java and if there's anything within `ClassLoaderHelper.mapAlternativeName`. I need to dig into the JDK, but it’s not looking promising. I wondered if `System.mapLibraryName` can handle a name with path separators, which we tested — it prepends/appends instead.\n\nThere was a thought about using a Unicode path separator for platforms like Linux, but it seems like a dead end. Testing on different platforms, like Mac and Linux, raises questions about coverage, so I’m considering how to adjust my Gradle settings for CI reporting.\n\n**Strengthening the Test for jnilib**\n\nI’m considering enhancing the current test by selecting a \"jnilib-mapped\" name specifically for platforms that support it, otherwise asserting that the fallback for the jnilib branch isn't available for that JDK. But it seems that’s not the best route.\n\nInstead, maybe I could introduce a custom test resource for `META-INF/native/libnetty_resource_probe.jnilib` and utilize Java's `System.loadLibrary` as a fallback. That might provide a better way to handle the situation!\n\n**Considering library names**\n\nI'm pondering whether `System.mapLibraryName` on Linux returns `.so`, and I wonder if the function behaves differently for names that start with \"lib\" and end with \".jnilib.\" It seems like it's worth testing both cases to see what we get. If there's any distinction in output, that could be essential information. Let’s dive into testing this further to clarify how the function handles different library extensions!", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_002b0d3570c69a040169f0ce55c160819cabe22ae3fccc4c8f\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABp8M52vvOYje0BAh7JWXkyZfmwJ2jRe-RChgHbMNJwIJZhnuJS0pIepB5BlMtoaAo0wleLiAGkocFv5w79IN2LQ_LAdXYFwvMUNtrSA8uwFGxk9LTf_nRjY5YYgM1Oduwyjl63xLQGdyJHFhtJ7N68ctgc-rNFeWT05haWXZ8cwcWfjRogNcDC5DVZcSVhp-jP3SHTu_yhLFt31BjDdhs38Dt9HqF-o4ZUN1LfEDQhCfXOFuWjdgn4DgXV9OZC891AR0RQy0QXkf3FRHPrHQna6lANWLeb1fPz3a-m7ltD1_CrLF0XGoQUZ8VlO6TjzMhz-DLYRsnZ9IamCUBO4X960eRJWZvXMBfKcP9yuoVo2S7oGfF23-UdFIDTTxc-y6xaUgI6B8ABepGflmcmFsBfg7Ix8-VeOjw8Y_pQ3X2vwthPBGtQ_U46qd4-INlMPu691obD90RwlXTTzUlm9yiFowJKByZrKTK_5Cfq4U0pk1Wy4qrZkR7dm3bBxGmunnac10Jxn7nOlnqylsChDemuiQMc3yRDJG3iWKvHygSFEttbpinaueroLrnZyxqZVE3UwNEziQaeIpFINFgKV_66652W1F9_8L5N9Su_xFmFcc1ie84OJDUP5tBRP5OjtEA6kJ2EkzsHPhiVQQreA4gq-p22JXSI3bP1eVzg54fwkOYy_stdffICvLG0C8qc3ylU-K1mYjaPejBDO7LPFiuXIExlrKxgC2Y1Tu1GoLJzAVsn0xDSkiDYvUaefldNBGGNm_FJmjbx5YAhyFg_T47puBSDNy_E3AzWD_2qiQ5u5_H8KO93hl0WUrrQYncIcb2NnfZN1HOdta_xcGDTNZ02Aj9KnV7iantWMX2eiAfn4Q1KUsiZsMNNwuxaH0vmneSPyxxKL_SQ399EaKnLDzPmgONMtOrscQZ-8P7RQUk-0TAPr41xU-7KVECHgdnLGWwkBCll-a0buCwNWNlvrrx3M3t2U7U0XxDxw_8OJJ7lWy0l9XafOacT-OdPV9A9JHOsgDvZ0UZ-mEqRYZX4jOLHfv38Fy5Pda6_4R2l1qxOVO2vft3vZXmxZSU9CVfhS4tyTxDsPe8ZwzgN8VSVH-_Z1YO9dLPuFMAVkhHcGXF6nPDAaxpj-BV19Ci2DFxxVQCfNflJetCuQwZoYmY2ixh-U8BAo5hjkuWJTU8xha6wKLxWZf_ILUpjZLiwtDO4up7Sga_MFXB6Nr7oElsFmDRet-XwZkYJS75QA00xv4u03R1Axpx9788_vZqBctz_CtRZcWEAW7Aw2Bsvodfaolvx163a4FkiHeoSwyCg6YXtLPauG5Wqz9vq2MEymr9bOd14YeqoH5HUyDeMImD_1n-A6jJxeFa2wrKc5G9P_Ul9A53aVqYnCwY0ox_1UgrIlTbxTI0X4riw70jifc9b4ULM14clwp6r9F8H77UUl2EzI8hJ8nyQgBQgSOq0XMZRIGYgWo56PC8ca6ofHJS3-M3dXmRuBT5EtVZin